column106: I lived in Arkansas for 40 years and experienced lots of warnings and tornadoes. I believe the current warning system is very effective.  Even an advanced system would not provide much of an advantage over the old system.  We are given soft warnings of possible tornadic activity when storms come. People in a state like Arkansas can sense rough weather coming and keep a radio handy.  I don't think the improved warnings would warrant the expense.  Spend improvement money on other projects - like how to prevent tornadoes.

column106: I have a college degree and a graduate degree.  I do not believe that most Americans will be able to comprehend probabilities, and that they prefer a zero or one rating, even if it means getting really short notice to take shelter.  So spending all that money will not give us better "results" in terms of lives saved, and in fact it might open the door to litigation by people who never really understood the difference between a 40% chance and a 0% chance of an uncertain event.
